  "So, this is basically how life evolves from the first microorganism."
  The old teacher paused, "Does anyone have a question?"

  It was currently the sixth morning period of class 1-E, which was also the
  final one before lunch break. Aside for some studious guys and gals
  conveniently located at the near-board desks, almost everyone's mind had dozed
  off elsewhere.

  While Misuzu High School was an academically-focused institution, it does not
  correlate with students actually paying focus during class. There were a
  couple of reasons for this.

  Firstly, the upper and lower echelon simply did
  not have any reason to listen to what the teachers had to say. While the top
  dogs had already studied the material way before stepping into the school, the
  bottom of the barrel, well, just did not care about the lesson at all. For
  them, the only way to pass exams were to indulge in something called
  "last-minute study", which was a technique that tended to be surprisingly
  efficient compared to its reputation.

  The second reason was the timing. It was only the third day of high school,
  and everyone, even including some teachers, was not ready for the change of
  pace. While some were still elated from the feeling of being admitted into an
  institute as prestigious as Misuzu three months after the results were
  announced, the others were still holding dear to the two-week spring vacation.
  The fact that lunch break was just around the corner did not help, either.

  And last but not least, it was due to the current material, namely Evolution
  and Microorganisms, as well as most topics of other subjects being taught in
  the first week, would hardly ever be brought up in exams. Internal exams,
  final exams, even university entrance exams, too. It was an unwritten rule to
  not mention any topic being taught so early into the program, as there was
  barely any material of such topics.

  Take evolution for example, what question could you even ask for such a topic?
  _Define evolution?_ Anyone could remember the definition by heart. _Are all
  mutations good or bad?_ Literally a viral science pop video could answer that.
  What else, showing the bone structure of a dog and a cat and asking students
  to compare that?

  Okay, I admit, if you think hard enough there could be some pretty tricky
  questions, but those had been reserved for first-year university curriculums.
  Even then, while it was cool to ask questions like "what is the source of
  life?", such question had already been answered since the 19th century, and
  more importantly, the topic did not make as much money as, let's say, anatomy
  and physiology for plastic surgery. After all, capital is the answer to
  everything.

  It had been a minute since the old teacher's conclusion, and no one seemed to
  be able to come up with anything of value. The silent atmosphere of the class
  was absolutely crushing everyone, except those whose minds were already on the
  clouds.

  The teacher knew exactly how much his teachings were silently disregarded by
  these adolescent kids. While microscopic germs and the process of natural
  selection was not really his forte, it still pissed him off that he could
  count those who actually listened to him for the past five minutes on his
  hand.

  Of course, it was not just class 1-E that behaved this way, but other classes
  seemed to give him the same treatment. Moreover, he himself was also impatient
  for the brief lunch break, too.

  "Well, since apparently no one really has a question, I guess I will give you
  guys some, then."

  He thumped the chalk onto the desk, which almost broke it in half. The sudden
  noise also brought back half of the class from the heavens, too. Everyone
  knew that trouble was coming up, even though freedom was approaching near in
  just a few minutes.

  Darting his eyes around the class, the biology teacher found numerous
  potential candidates for his upcoming question. However, none of which really
  stood out as a certain black-hair girl on a desk four rows from the front, who
  was still looking out the window.

  "You!" He pointed at the distracted girl, who had yet to regain her
  consciousness, "Can you tell the difference between bacteria and viruses?"

  Even though her classmates were giving her worried looks, the girl was still
  daydreaming. It was not until the girl sitting below her poked a pen onto
  her back that she regained her senses. She quickly stood up and got a grasp on
  the situation, but even then it was still too late.

  "Could you share the answer to the whole class?" The teacher prompted in a
  heartwarming yet terrifying tone.

  "Erm..." She darted her eyes in search of salvation, yet ended up finding
  nothing of value. Let alone the answer, even of the question itself was she not
  aware.

  With no other choices, she muttered in a quiet yet clear tone, "Excuse me, can
  you repeat..."

  "Stand there!" The teacher strictly proclaimed, "You, don't let me repeat the
  question again."

  He pointed at the brown-haired girl who was poking at the black-hair girl from
  earlier. While she was still keeping tabs of the lesson, it was apparent that
  she was letting his words go in one ear and out the other.

  She hastily stood up, yet what she could mutter was a few words,

  "Viruses are smaller than bacteria, I think..."

  "So according to you, pandoraviruses are bigger than mycoplasmas, right?"

  "Uhm..."

  While bacteria in general were larger than viruses, size alone was not the
  main distinction between the two microbial classes. This was why he gave her
  such a cherry-picked counterexample. Of course, the girl herself did not even
  know what "pandoraviruses" and "mycoplasmas" were, so she could only stand
  there in silence.

  The old teacher sighed in disappointment, as the rest of the class silently
  praying in their heads for him not to call them next.

  "You kids thought that, 'I got to Misuzu, the most prestigious prep school of
  this nation, I'm so smart!', and decided to slack off, right? You don't take
  anyone else seriously and think you all are the so-called 'cream of the crop'
  ..."

  There, I cut you the long rambling. That day's lunch break was delayed 10
  minutes due to the anger of a biology teacher. Spoiler alert, but not a
  surprise, his next lesson would be taken very seriously by everyone in class
  1-E, especially by those two girls who got called up today.

